data.content:
These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:

---

**Case 1 — `&&` with `dynamic` and interface operators**

`&&` is synthesized from `operator false(x) ? x : operator &(x, y)`. The compiler now partially resolves this pattern at compile time even when the right operand is `dynamic`. It finds `operator true`/`operator false` on `IFilter`, commits to that resolution path, then fails because `IFilter` has no `operator &`. Previously, the whole expression was deferred to the runtime binder.

**Fix:** Add `operator &` to `IFilter`, or avoid `&&` with `dynamic`:

```csharp
interface IFilter
{
    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;
    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;
    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x; // add this
}
```

Or replace the short-circuit expression with explicit logic:

```csharp
void Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    dynamic combined = IFilter.op_False(left) ? (dynamic)left : left & right;
}
```

---

**Case 2 — `ref readonly` return lambda and CS0518**

CS0518 means a **predefined type required by the compiler is missing** from your target framework. In C# 15, `ref readonly` return lambdas require the compiler to synthesize an anonymous delegate type encoding the `ref readonly` return in metadata. This needs a new predefined attribute (likely in `System.Runtime.CompilerServices`) that only ships with the .NET 11 base class library.

**Most likely cause:** your project still targets an older TFM. Check your `.csproj`:

```xml
<!-- Must be net11.0, not an older TFM -->
<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>
```

If you can't retarget, use a named delegate or a method instead:

```csharp
delegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();

static RefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;
// or just use a static method
static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;
```
